There's enough discourse on how glamorous and exciting the job seem to be, and I have never taken the opportunity for granted 🙏🏻 

But there is needed space for people in the industry to be more vulnerable-- and more supported.

Be prepared to become your job. 

All of a sudden, your entire identity can be swept up into your job, and a lot of aspects of your life can start to feel transactional (i.e. your interests, hobbies, the people you spend time with, who you present yourself as online, etc).

There are a lot of instances where shit happens and you just can't take it personally-- and that can be really tough advice to follow. 

I've cried more at work than I care to admit in the past two years (though WFH certainly makes it easier than ever to cry at work..)
No matter how collaborative you want to be, there is always a clear winner and a clear loser in a deal.  In order to 'win', sometimes your elbows really need to be quite sharp in your dealings.

Despite meeting more people than you could ever possibly fit in your calendar, you'll also feel quite lonely and isolated most of the time. 

Most VC investment teams are quite small, and VCs usually operate (meetings, research, diligence, form opinions) solo.

Being a VC inherently means having the self-confidence and self-importance to step into a role with a lot of perceived power and authority. 

If you can't get there due to intense imposter syndrome, it will only get worse (I've struggled the most with this, and still struggle).

I’m no expert on penny stocks/ how to get them publicly listed/ how to gain custodianship of these defunct vehicles..but imagine there are loopholes there!

Did a quick googling of his name, and some of the results that came up in penny-stock subreddits were..less than flattering- he seems to frequently run these shells under the guise of forgotten about Chinese company vehicles. Tongji seems to fit the bill.

https://t.co/DnnORCEKcC https://t.co/3z3iWgbfyY
Fast forward to 2019- a third party by the name of Joseph Arcaro somehow was granted custodianship over this forgotten shell company by appealing to a NV judge https://t.co/fnrv8URqbU

Fwiw companies set up off shore vehicles all the time for all kinds of reasons, and in 2006, two companies by the same name (Tongji) were set up in the US: One in Nevada, the other in Colorado. The one in Colorado was eventually dissolved, but unfortunately the NV was forgotten.
“Tongji Healthcare Group” as reported in these PR press releases looks like one of many shell companies w that was set up in 2006 by a legitimate Chinese medical group, Nanning Tongji Hospital, Inc.

So for now, I'm patiently waiting, learning, trying new products, and ultimately continue to be optimistic in the long term for the future of crypto as an asset class (which has its ups and downs), knowing that there will be a ton of bumps in the road ahead, and that's also ok.

Other areas like healthcare, insurance, real estate, etc-- these are all complicated areas with a ton of regulatory burden and inefficiency.

And yet I continue to see new businesses built in these industries (which all have been around for much longer than crypto has).

As much as we try to abstract away the complicated part of interacting with crypto apps or incorporating crypto to UX via better designs, the fact of the matter is that a lot of these crypto concepts are still weird, hard to understand, and at times unnecessarily complicated.

In the short term: the fiat to crypto / traditional fintech to crypto gap will remain near impossible in the meantime (especially in the U.S); crypto apps only used by crypto-native users; and honestly, maybe that's ok for now!

Though- I don't really see this as a nail in the coffin for all crypto companies trying to bridge the crypto// "traditional" financial asset class. 

It just means that now we have more information to build the next version of a heavily-regulated financial product (I.e. coinbase)

In the meantime, I think this will encourage DEXs, crypto-to-crypto "swaps" or transactions (we are already seeing the explosion in the various defi products; more value locked in defi every day); and less of the traditional fintech biz methods applied to crypto businesses.

The reality here now is that any crypto businesses that want onboard the next million non-crypto native users by touching fiat or traditional fintech products will have to navigate intense financial regulations/ requirements. But these headaches happen in other industries too.

-- especially if it touches "traditional" asset classes (here it was the Stock/ ETF thing that really got Abra in trouble), no matter the underlying tech (transactions done on the bitcoin blockchain/ contracts created for each tx), and no matter where in the world ops get moved.

One narrative within crypto today is that it is financial engineering on steroids- a statement that I partially agree with. But that also means businesses built around that narrative will fall under the same regulatory scrutiny as traditional financial institutions--

But the most important thing is also to accept that it’s impossible to predict the future, and sometimes decision- making is as much calculation as it is also just...part of life. And there are things that you’ll never be able to control fully :)

Sometimes when I work backwards  from the *future*, (where will I be 2 or 5 years from today if I go with choice A?) instead of thinking in the present (here are the pros and cons of these two choices as it applies *today*), the answer becomes clear.

I’ve been thinking a lot about decision- making lately, and have found that the most effectively way is to ask your future self: 

“A year from today, looking back at this exact moment, will I regret choosing A?”

Then do the same for choice B. And trust your gut feeling!

If you are reading this as a male in a professional position that is powerful& respected and want to help, here are some ways that I’ve found really helpful in situations like the ones I’ve describe above:
Having mentors and friends who are also women in very male-dominated industries help in terms of having that emotional support network and asking for advice on what to do in certain situations.

And sometimes it’s the imposter syndrome (which I’ve talked about before) that gets compounded even further during meetings when I become hyper aware of the fact that I’m the only woman in the room and no one bothers to really address me when talking.
Or someone will come into my office for a meeting with me and be visibly disappointed that none of my other male colleagues are in the office.

But then I’ll get copied on an email for a meeting, and the recipient (male) will immediately email me asking when one of my (male) colleagues will be free to chat- even though the intent for the email was clearly for him to meet/ chat with me.

For the most part, being a woman in a heavily male-dominated industry is likely better today than it has ever been, and I think about the opportunities that have been available to me that my mother or grandmother could not have accessed at my age.

The majority of the men in my professional life whom I interact with on a regular basis are kind, paitient, and respectful. 

But every once in a while I am reminded very starkly of the implicit sexist bias that exists from small gestures to more overt acts.

Anyway...I don’t know where I was going with this except that I’m really happy to be myself today in this city &  world and no longer feel so invisible. 

And I’m really happy that as an adult I’ve finally found “my” people, including this slice on the internet with all of you 🤗

I see so many “wish I had your confidence” and “wow I could never put myself out there like that” comments- and honestly, I think it’s only because for so long I never had to care about what other people thought of me or what I did- because no one cared either!

Hilariously, I didn’t even get great grades. Honestly this isn’t even a “I had no friends or hobbies but I got great grades” situation. 

I had a few subjects I liked a lot and was good at, but for the most part my grades were pretty average.

I wasn’t an athlete, I wasn’t into theatre, and I wasn’t artistically or musically talented. I liked reading books, but that wasn’t really something any other 12-18 year olds (or schools!) cared about. 

Sort of figured I was just...boring, and being invisible suited me.

This actually isn’t meant to be a sad story or anything; I wasn’t sad as a teenager, nor did I ever feel like I needed to be anything else. 

But it did affect my sense of self worth and confidence and made me think that ”success” had to be a certain way and that was not me.

Then high school. I didn’t get bullied in high school, but it was something else: I felt very, very invisible. I wasn’t particularly disliked or liked- just never really thought about. 

I had one friend that I hung out with and when she was busy I’d just keep to myself.

Lots of meals by myself in the hallways. Begged the school librarian to let me help her sort books so I’d have something to do during breaks between classes. Reads TONS of books- and spent a lot of time in the computer lab!

I transferred into a lot of different schools growing up (sometimes in the middle of a school year) and never really felt like I fit in anywhere. 

Didn’t help that in middle school there was one particular group of girls who always made fun of my clothes/shoes/ hair.

So I kept a (few) diaries 📔 that I wrote in every single day from the day I turned 12 till I went to college. 

I still have them today! I haven’t read them in a while but spent this weekend flipping through them and...damn I am so fucking proud of me today 😭

I still don't know or why how my cold application got picked with zero "ins" or connections- but it's changed my entire life and career trajectory. 

So....if you're thinking about getting into venture, apply to the USV program. You never know what can happen.
Through the USV interview process, I met the amazing @aweissman, who has remained a friend and mentor to me till this day-- and later on, became the reason I got connected with @notationcapital.

I didn't expect anything from the application, since-- well, I didn't have any connections in tech or venture, I didn't really have a huge twitter/online presence-- oh, and I was still in law school back then!

Surprisingly, I got an email two weeks later asking for an interview.

Quick storytime: a few years ago, I came across this same tweet from USV calling for applications. 

I had no friends in venture/ tech, but I was obsessed with crypto. I threw in an application (I wrote a response on bitcoin, and then also submitted a video about crypto lol).

One common advice I've seen is that warm intros are the only way into an interview at a top venture fund.

From personal experience, I can say that it is not true. Take your time with the app. Demonstrate a true passion for something. I promise USV will give you a fair chance.

Btw— combined with the EOS case, it sort of also showed that as long as you register your securities offerings (this doesn’t seem to be in much dispute now), do your KYC, and can show that you’ve built something, the SEC had no reason to shut you down entirely.

So WHAT DOES THIS MEAN? Well, I guess it's more about what was NOT said in the settlement, which is the 2018 Siafund sale done under Reg D and Siacoins(the one being traded on exchanges)...might be okay? 

And holy-implications (the good kind!) if that is the case.
BTW I am no investor in Sia nor do I have any stake in the company, but it seems to be that teams that actually builds product are getting off pretty lightly from the SEC.

I don't want to read too much into tea leaves here, but what the SEC really did was just a slap on the wrist for the 2014 sale..but left the $1.5 million worth of the later token sale alone? 

And as far as I know, none of Sia's operations are affected.

So far, so good. 

BUT I do think it's interesting (and weird?) that 

1. the SEC went after a super small amount of $$ raised from 2014 (well before the DAO report, btw); 

2. that not one word of the 2018 Reg D Siafunds sale or Siacoins was mentioned or even addressed.

What the SEC went after here is the super low-hanging fruit of the 120k raised back in 2014, which is undeniable a security. 

Sia had to cough up twice that amount as penalties, and basically agreed to contact the SEC prior to issuing any new type of token in the future.

SIDENOTE on Sia's token structure (which is confusing af): 

Sia implemented a two-token network—Siafunds (the rev-share token) and Siacoins (their utility token). Anytime someone buys storage on the network, a small transaction fee is distributed to the Siafunds.

So from what I understand, Sia did two entirely different rounds of fundraising: there was one from 2014 back when David (the founder)raised his 'sianotes' in ~ 120k from a forum; and then there was the "siafunds" Reg-D sale from 2018.

A lot of the U.S. crypto-related SEC enforcement actions/ settlements in 2019 have been swift, and largely have dealt with pretty scammy actors.

But the one with Sia is particularly interesting (and different!) to me for a few reasons..

@jamescmlin Also I think people have different definitions and personal views of what “sucks” in a job. I can say that I love my job but I have friends who would hear about my day to day and be like..ok well good for you but your jobs sounds awful to me.

@jamescmlin I don’t think that pay and personal fulfillment has to be mutually exclusive. But my point was more about figuring out the “what would make you enjoy your job” part and then optimize for that. If it’s just money, and money = fulfillment, then one should optimize for that.
@wes_dewayne I agree that defining yourself by your work is a very one-dimensional self-identity framework, but I don’t think it’s exclusive to American culture!

@richard_tull 100 agree- and I guess one point I didn’t have space to make was that money/ hours/ pay and fulfillment don’t necessary have to be mutually exclusive. Also, my advice obviously targets those who are in a privileged position to begin with and makes some sweeping assumptions!

Anyway, if you're unhappy in your role right now, and feel really frustrating/ confused/ stuck, I promise you that it's a normal feeling, and that it's okay to take your time to figure things out. Just make sure you are prioritizing the right things as you take that next step! 💫

I've said this before, but I really do think that the reason why job-searching is so exhausting is because it's less about what you think it is (pay/title- though that definitely matters) and more about a lesson in yourself (what am I good at, and what makes me feel fulfilled).

The other thing that I tell people is to dig deep and take time to figure out your own 'superpower'. Some of my most creative and extraverted friends are in a cubicle at large corporations. They're great at their jobs, but would likely excel in a more creative and social role.

I feel like so many people focus on the external factors (wage/location/industry/hours) and not on the values that matter more personally (more creativity? more learning? more/less autonomy?).

The difference between the two is in intrinsic motivation + personal fulfillment.

By the way, I don't think the problem is with people being complacent or not trying to change their job situation. I think the problem is with identifying the 'Why'.

A lot of my friends will move cities or industries, only to come back to the same unhappy conclusion.

Spent the weekend w/ a large group of friends and every single person, regardless of industry, talked about how much they hate their jobs- but 'whatever, it's fine, everyone hates it'. 

It really shouldn't be fine or normal. We spend at least 50% of our waking hours at our jobs.

My final point: 

No one is invincible. And it's easy to think that when you might know others who have done the same thing and got away with it totally unscathed. But it really isn't worth it.

There is a saying in Chinese: 杀鸡给猴看- "killing the chicken to scare the monkey' i.e. make an example out of someone in order to scare/threaten the others.

When it comes to insider trading charges, it really doesn't matter how little money you made from that trade.

The reality is that it truly is hard to catch an insider trading case red-handed, with hard proof.

And that is why when an illegal trading activity can be matched up to a person, those prosecutors will get after it hard.

When I had worked on insider trading cases at the SEC, I spent most of my time pouring over trading data and patterns.

I know this situation might sound so obvious, but I promise you that every single person who does this truly thinks that they won't be the ones to get caught.

Unbeknownst to you, the SEC has been monitoring all activity related to this company for months now. And they find your trade in no time. The next thing you know, you are facing both civil charges and looking at jail time.

The day of the acquisition finally comes, and on the day of the announcement, you sell those options for an easy profit.

Boom, so easy. And hey, you can't be the only one who's done it, right? Plus, who's gonna care about the couple thousand dollars that you made?

With this piece of information, maybe you go off and buy call options in a company that you confidentially know is going to get acquired. And maybe you hide this account from your employer-- because well, you know someone else who doesn't report all their accounts, either.

I know we all know that insider trading is wrong and illegal. But I think that sometimes we do things because we *think* we can get away with it.

For example, maybe you come across a piece of confidential information. You've seen it. So have the 50+ other people on your team.

Sincere PSA:

Breaking federal securities laws has serious consequences. Something like insider trading carries both civil and criminal (i.e. jail sentence) penalties.

It doesn't matter how little you profit or how infrequently you do it. Once you're caught, you're done.

Be confident in the work that you have done. Dig up all the positive professional feedback you've received (and don't you put yourself down), and use that to arm yourself!

The not so great news is, well, we’re still not really getting answers and these firms must continue to play the waiting game. 

Glass half full? Slow the steady wins the race. 💪🏻Glass half empty? Fuckkkkkk trying to build a compliant crypto business here is complicated af. 😭

The good news is, the agency does acknowledge certain difficulties and challenges that crypto broker dealers are facing, and are not coming down and saying that every single requirement must be complied with the traditional way.

So..... the ultimate TLDR? 

Well, those who are sitting at the one year + mark waiting for their broker dealer license to be approved may have to wait longer. I’ve only highlighted a handful of issues that the agencies are grappling with.

But b/c SIPA has a different definition of ‘securities’ than the securities law definition (ie Howey- i know, this is so fun) some customers w assets that don’t meet the securities definition under SIPA would basically not get protection and get fucked in case of liquidation.

Concerns re investor protection: 

Traditionally, a broker-dealer that goes totally bankrupt and can’t return funds would be liquidated in accordance with SIPA (which gives securities customers have a first priority claim to cash and securities held by the firm). [cont.]

Also notes that the record keeping rules broker-dealer to evidence the existence of digital asset securities for the purposes of the broker-dealer’s regulatory books, records, and financial statements, including supporting schedules would be difficult.

Interesting caveat from the SEC, where they acknowledge that those who wish to custody crypto assets “may find it challenging to comply with the BD financial responsibility rules w/o putting in place significant technological enhancements and solutions unique to [crypto]. “

Generally speaking, the agencies are not super concerned with noncustodial activities (ie OTC in secondary markets)— but entities that perform functions to facilitate the clearance & settlement of transactions in digital asset securities may have to register as a clearing agency.

Some issues that were mentioned:

+ Re: custody- the fact that a broker-dealer maintains the private key != exclusive control. (e.g., it may not be able to demonstrate that no other party has a copy of the private key and could transfer the digital asset security)

The SEC + FINRA just released a joint statement essentially explaining why FINRA has taken its sweet time (that is an understatement) to approve any pending broker-dealer license. 

TLDR: still too many open questions for the agencies to get comfortable

Anyway writing all of this and saying 'teens' and 'kids' have made me feel super ancient and deeply 'uncool' this AM

On Snapchat (2): I think that my generation (later-Millenials) entirely over-saturated the world with picture perfect realities (i.e if this isn't perfect I won't post it to social media)- but with finstas, snaps , etc-- I think social media will get more authentic with time.

On Snapchat (1): If you ask any of my friends (in their 20s), they'd tell you that Snapchat is dead and that Instagram has totally eclipsed that usage. But I think Snap is still the #1 communicating tool for a lot of teens. (Streaks, unbeatable AR effects, disappearing messages)
On Twitter: This is just funny to me, because a lot of middle/ high schoolers think of Twitter as an 'app for grown-ups'. (god, that makes me feel SO old).

On TikTok (4): So I think that the lesson there is-- the sense of community ONLINE is real. But also, don't be *that* adult this summer asking 'hey are you kids on tiktok'-- they likely won't admit to it, and it doesn't get you any cool points. :)

On TikTok (2): Of course, I think Tiktok will see a spike in creators in the next month or two, given that most of its user are on summer break (more free time with friends). Even though it's not 'cool' to say that you're on TikTok, it's still a fun thing to create skits/ dances.

On TikTok (1): Despite what you may have read or heard, a lot of teens view Tiktok as a 'guilty pleasure'-- i.e not something you'd admit you spend time on (or creating). The best analogy I can think of is Yelp- everyone uses it, no one admits to writing reviews.

On crypto (2): So the lesson here is more around teaching kids about investing and saving early on. They want USD because they want to immediately be able to buy cool clothes/ shoes etc, and think of 'investing' as a grown-up thing.

On crypto (1): if you asked (US) teenagers if they prefer to receive $100 in USD or in bitcoin, most of them will still say USD. That's because they see bitcoin as an 'investment' (like stocks). They don't have an issue accepting the fact that bitcoin is a valuable asset.

Building the 'next XYZ for Gen Z' means to actually go and use and read whatever it is that the smartphone-native generation spends most of their time on instead of pontificating on what they might like/ hate/ use/ think. Examples: crypto, tiktok, twitter, snapchat. 👇

6/ Last but not least, have fun. Remember that you are on the panel because you know your shit, and we are all here to learn. Everyone else is just as nervous. You got this!!!!! 💪🏻

5a/ Instead of 'omg that was horrendous', focus on the small stuff. Is it that you move your hands too much when you talk? That can be easily fixed. Do you say 'um' too much? That's also solvable!! These are small things that you CAN fix. Nothing too bad :)
5/ Overachiever move: force yourself to listen/ watch your talk afterwards. Don't be too critical, but also take notes of the stuff that you want to change, and VISUALIZE it for your next talk.

4/ BREATHE!! Controlled breathing while on stage can help level set in terms of being more present, but also can help with physical symptoms. My heart always beats super fast and my palms get sweaty. Take slow, deep breaths in between your talk.

3a/ Talking to other people about something totally unrelated to the topic helps! It distracts me from my doom day scenarios, and also loosens me up in terms of my voice, my posture, and my ease around other people. Think about it as a warm up before the big game :)

3/ Make some small talk before you have to go on stage. If you're an overthinker like me, I tend to invent worst-case scenarios right before i have to go on stage (tripping, falling, saying something stupid)-- and most times than not it'll just stress me out unnecessarily.

2e/ In reality, you know enough not to need your bullet points, but just the knowledge of having them might help with nerves right before you get on stage. Tell yourself-- you know this stuff, PLUS you've prepared!!

2d/ The reason why you practice so much is that EVEN IF stage fright takes over or if I totally blank on stage, I've practiced enough that muscle memory just takes over. The same goes for talking! Plus, think of bullet points as a security blanket.

2c/ I used to do choreographed dance in high school, and the main ingredient in having a good performance is practice again and again along with music. Sometimes in the middle, there may be a freestyle section.

2b/ Write down those 3-4 bullet points on a flashcard, in your notes app, or something easy you can glance at the day before + the day of. Don't bring it on stage!! The reason I do this is because it helps me stay on track when nerves take over.

2a/ Because panel talks are more conversational, there's no point in trying to memorize an entire piece of a talk. Instead, write down the 3-4 bullet points that you want to be able to hit, no matter what.

2/ Practice! The good news is that before a panel, the moderator will generally host a call that will help you get a general idea of the topics that will be discussed. Even if not, there are some ways to prepare.

1d/ Example 2: this sounds dumb, but knowing how I will sit helps me to think about what to do with my hands during a panel when other people are talking. Just visualizing what I will physically look like on stage +  minimizing distractions in advance really helps with nerves.

1c/ Example: if I will be sitting on a high stool, I will wear pants > dress. Holding both a water bottle and a mic while on a high stool is totally impractical so I will leave my water bottle off stage instead of having to worry about it on stage.

1b/ There are two practical reasons for visualizing. One, it helps me decide on what to wear. The last thing I want to do is to adjust my clothing while on stage- it's distracting + makes me look nervous. Two, it will help me figure out what I need to pay attention to re: posture

1a/ Before a talk, I will try and get a visual idea of what the stage will look like, what the set up will be like (what kind of chairs? Am i getting mic'ed up or holding a mic?), and where on the stage I will be.

1/ Visualisation! A lot of athletes I know tell me that before a match, they actually will try and visualize themselves physically on the court/ in the race and having a good game. The same goes for public speaking!

There are more factors to consider re: is the token less likely to be a security, and I won't copy paste or paraphrase them here, but its in page 9-10 of the framework https://t.co/gfSmFGFn55

(real talk im tired)

21a/ 

+ token holders can immediately use it for its intended functionality
on the network

+ if the issuer facilitates the creation of a secondary market, transfers of the digital asset may only be made by and among users of the platform

21/ To wrap it up, what are some things that make the tokens LESS likely to be a security under the Howey test?

+ both network and token fully functional and decentralized.
+ Prospects for appreciation in the token are limited (ie people dont expect to HODL for $$$)

20/ Important question: what if the token sale was a security (and you didnt register), but now you truly think that your tokens should be re-evaluated since you really don't think it's a security in its form today? *uhemETHERuhem*

Consider these factors then: https://t.co/gpy4bf9R5P

19/ Some pretty obvious examples (translating the legalese): If you, as an issuer, successfully shill tf out of your tokens, that's creating a reasonable expectation of profit for your bagholders. If you as an issuer create a trading market for the token, same thing.

18/ Under the Howey test, if an asset price appreciates as a result solely from external market forces (such as general inflationary trends or the economy), that's not profit. I'm not going into all the factors, but think about what DRIVES your token price appreciation. https://t.co/IX81u50EI2
17/ Let's now move onto "Reasonable Expectation of Profits" bc lol this fund never ends (and now that I am accountable I can't give up half way) https://t.co/24WA2buA95

16/ Points 13-16 really is to say: the SEC has some ideas as to what a 'decentralized network' looks like, and if you have a team who not only issues, sells, and promotes the tokens but also engages in the above, that's (obviously) not decentralized enough.

15/ An affiliated party are those who created a market for the price of the digital assets (ie limiting supply through buybacks, burning), or plays a lead or central role in deciding governance issues, code updates, etc.

13/ If you, as the purchaser of the tokens-- reasonably rely on others-- SEC defines it as a promoter, sponsor, or other third party (or affiliated group of third parties) -- to take on significant developments/ changes to the network, that meets most of it. *Keyword: affiliated*

12/ The third prong of the Howey test *i.e. Reasonable Expectation of Profits Derived from Efforts of Others", is the more complicating factor. 

Some important considerations: reliance on others to make your tokens more valuable is generally what they mean by this.

11/ We know already that each analysis is highly dependent on the facts and circumstances. The first two elements of the Howey test are also the easier ones to analyze: did you sell tokens for $$, and was there a central team developing it? The SEC thinks that most cases, yes. https://t.co/WnstBoFmQP

12/ To me, these reports show that we still have so much work to do on narratives, education, and UX/UI. Given how low trust is in mainstream media, we have an opportunity (and responsibility!) as an industry to push better and accurate information out to the broader market.

11/ I definitely appreciated these two reports that the FCA commissioned. They were fair, asked good questions, and did not end with any over-hyped dangers to the overall markets, or how we should stay away from crypto assets.

10/ This part is really important: 

Most consumers used Coinbase to buy their crypto because it was often referenced in media. BUT!!  Although some people wanted to use platforms other than Coinbase, they were often unable to understand how they worked.

OK HI UX/UI IMPORTANCE https://t.co/lUZyvleYvq

9/ Majority of those buyers first heard about crypto from friends/family who claimed to have made a profit. Asked about the sources that they trust re: cryptoassets, most agreed that they distrust mainstream media coverage (but were confident in their own 'instincts').

8/ Now onto the in-depth interviews conducted towards those who either hold crypto or are seriously thinking about buying crypto. (Sample size: 31)

Most of their reasons for buying: to make short term profits, or because of FOMO.

7/ One quick note: this shows to me that there is still very much a huge issue with the way that we discuss crypto, particularly to average consumers who have no idea how to think about this industry and the various crypto assets.

6/ That being said, the general attitude towards cryptocurrency is quite friendly. 71% of crypto owners agreed that a cryptocurrency purchase is a risk they are willing to take. 62% believe that they are alternative investments to those offered in mainstream finance (!) https://t.co/dpuaQriC0U
5/ Many also seemed to have a sense that they were investing in tangible assets, due to the language and imagery associated with cryptoassets, such as ‘mining’ and ‘coin’.
4/ Many consumers overestimated their knowledge of cryptoassets- for example: several of those interviewed talked of wanting to buy a ‘whole’ coin, not realizing that they could buy just part of one.

3/ Interesting findings: the FCA interviewed about 2,132 UK consumers (16 y/o+). Based on that, they concluded that about 73% of UK consumers don’t know what a 'cryptocurrency' is or are unable to define it- and those who are aware of are likely to be men aged between 20 and 44. https://t.co/eIAx9bXuD8

2/ While the reports generally found that there is a general poor level of understanding of crypto among UK consumers, the FCA still concludes that—  the overall scale of harm is ’not as high as previously thought”.

1a/ The link to the two research reports can be found here- one is a more in-depth interview of those who currently hold crypto, and the other is a broader national sentiment survey re: crypto.  

https://t.co/34ds4XpmYi

Since I can't help but tie everything to questions in crypto-building: 

Think about your users, and not in an abstract way. Find ways to engage with them & get their feedback.

Most importantly, humanize your product. Tech != impersonal, and crypto is a people-powered ecosystem.

Shipping product is important, but so is meaningful engagement with your users/ consumers/ potential hires. I remember seeing a job posting once and there was a section for 'Who you will be working with' w/ people profiles. Great move to humanize the recruiting process.

Glossier's "every single person is an influencer" marketing take is also super thoughtful. For example, before I buy something, I would totally trust a stranger's review over an algo recommended product. Using your consumers as your spokesperson > paying for celebrities.

And Glossier is actively building out a platform *for* their users. What Glossier does really well is serving the customer to interact with each other. In stores or online, people are answering each other's questions about the product. IMO that's just brilliant.

As we move more towards 'digital everything', I think that humanizing a process-- any process, really-- will become even more important. The magic of Glossier is really in capturing that sort of authenticity that consumers/ users have started to crave more.

Glossier's "cult-like" consumer following is built on top of those two main points. When users feel heard and connected, they are more likely to engage and share feedback. 

The point "Amazon really solved buying, but it killed shopping in the process" totally resonated with me.

I finally had a chance to listen to @karaswisher interview @EmilyWWeiss (CEO of Glossier), two major takeaways:

+ Your users = your lifeline
+ Humanity is extraordinarily important in connecting with your users (this is especially important for tech companies)

https://t.co/kfO12fKCnh

The complicated thing is that-- your phone contains sensitive records that will reveal far more information than the most exhaustive search of your house. How can that sort of broad power be limited by your right to privacy as under the fourth amendment?

But emails are instantaneous and happen along machine communications. And to confine the corners of machine communication within laws that are for the physical space is difficult. Then you throw in stuff like: passcode locks on your phone, encryption, P2P file sharing, etc.

When it comes to the internet and networks, the line between privacy and open/public information is much harder to define. For example, letters in transit are not expected to have a right to privacy, because the intermediaries are human (mailman) and prone to delivery errors.

In other words-- in the physical world, the expectation of privacy hinges on two major factors: 1. The subjective expectation of privacy, and 2. The expectation that society is willing to recognize as reasonable.

In the physical world, the line between privacy and open/public information is pretty obvious- when you close the door to your apartment (h/t @soonaorlater for that comparison), you have that reasonable expectation of privacy.

The online world and the “real” world are different in many respects, and the rules that apply to searches in the “real” world cannot simply be applied to digital searches — whether searches of online networks or searches of physical computers.

"Code v2" by @lessig -- even after all these years -- is still such a thought-provoking read. 

One major question I've been pondering lately: how should the fourth amendment protections against unreasonable search and seizures extend to the digital space?

10/ So-- aside from Switzerland, Malta, Singapore, Hong Kong, and the U.K., I'm interested to see which other countries will issue comprehensive guidance/ frameworks for the crypto asset space in this next year in an effort to encourage fintech + innovation in their country.

9/ Though other regulators in the world still look to the U.S. regulators and their crypto guidance as a reference, it's clear that they are taking one step forward and issuing sandboxes, regulations, or guidance without waiting around.

8/ The U.S. government shutdown will result in so much backlog and delays across all sectors- I am pessimistic about any meaningful progress that could be made on the crypto frontier once everything is back up and running (if ever..)

7/ But this also may be how and why other countries (particularly SE Asia or HK/Taiwan) can jump into the crypto sector by providing frameworks and guidance that are easier to navigate or, in some cases, construct from ground zero.

6/ The SEC has been so vilified by the crypto-community in the U.S. due to definitions that are rooted in the way that the legal structure is set. The U.S. legal system is based on precedents, and to overrule that usually takes a shit ton of time and legal resources. 🤷🏻‍♀️

5/ In addition, Hong Kong has launched sandboxes for crypto exchanges, and seem fairly willing to work with the crypto community to shape the regulations into something that makes more sense (likely in response to criticism that the regulations are too hard to comply w)

4/ In fact, the Hong Kong regulators (and it seems like the UK here too) are pretty comfortable with the position that not all tokens = securities, and that not everything token-related would fall under their jurisdiction. (Screenshot from a November guidance by the HK SFC). https://t.co/79CNwtMXQM
3/ This is because the Howey Test & its broad definition of an 'investment contract' is unique to the U.S. only. Other jurisdictions do not have as broad of a definition within their legal limits.

2/ Last month, I went and met with some folks from Hong Kong's SFC (Securities and Future Commission), who have released regulatory guidance for crypto exchanges & funds. What's interesting to me: non-U.S. regulators are less likely to focus on the 'everything= security' thing.

1/ The U.K.'s FAC (Financial Conduct Authority) released some pretty important (draft) guidelines today outlining how they are thinking around regulation of crypto assets.

10/ Two more things: the rules encourage self-regulation as a way to increase legitimacy for the blockchain/crypto industry. Also, to go the ICP registration path is actually a lot more flexible for blockchain companies to continue to operate in China, since burden to do is low.

9/ Most of these regulations are not that out of the norm for any internet companies in China, but I think the one problematic point is the way that the rule over "users" is written, as it includes community members of a crypto project (even if the project is based abroad!)

8/ This also imposes certain recordkeeping requirements, including having a copy of a 6-month log of user content and comments (this probably includes community members in a slack/discord). These records will be turned over to relevant agencies if an investigation opens.

7/ Also: any "blockchain service provider" must *not* service users who do not provide information to verify their real identity (i.e. phone #, ID #, or their company ID #. This is common for most internet companies in China, but could be difficult here.

6/ Think of it as a 'give us your company + officer information so you can do business in China as an internet content provider and so we have someone to go after if there is anything shady/illegal that result from your services"

4/ In order to obtain such a license, companies will have to abide by certain requirements, such as providing information on its business name, service type, ID addresses, service jurisdiction within 10 business days of service.

3/ China will be regulating crypto companies via its ICP registration process, which is its way of regulating most internet companies in China. So, in order to do business in China, blockchain companies will have to register for an ICP (Internet Content Provider) license.

2b/

+ "Blockchain information service users" refer to an organization or an individual. The big question here: can this be construed to also include community members of a token project?

2a/ Definitions:

+ "Blockchain information services providers" refer to those organizations or companies who provide support to blockchain tech companies or the general public. Some think that this is broad enough to cover foreign subsidiary or even foundations.

2/ Definitions:

+ "Blockchain information services" are those who provide information service to the general public via their apps/ web services that are based on blockchain technology.

1/ Back in October, China’s “Internet regulator” put out draft regulatory guidelines for “"Blockchain information service and providers”. 

As of this week, those guidelines are formalized and will take effect beginning February 15th.
